    <!-- 2. The story -->
    <section class="section pt-0">
      <div class="container container--narrow">
        <h2 class="mb-4">📖 The story</h2>

        <div class="card mb-6">
          <p class="mb-4 text-secondary">
            In January 2016, the French Ministry of Culture published a damning report:
            <strong>it is impossible to type proper French on an AZERTY keyboard</strong> —
            the layout used on virtually every computer in France. No native accented capitals,
            no French quotation marks, no œ ligature...
          </p>
          <p class="mb-4 text-secondary">
            Following this report, AFNOR (the French standards body) was commissioned to create a new standard.
            In 2019, the <a href="https://norme-azerty.fr" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NF Z71-300 standard</a> was published. But this official solution
            imposes <strong>too abrupt a break</strong> with the Windows AZERTY,
            only partially addresses developers' needs, and <strong>has struggled to catch on</strong>:
            very few compatible keyboards are sold and adoption remains marginal.
          </p>
          <div class="page-presse__story-split mb-4">
            <p class="text-secondary">
              Meanwhile, <strong>Antoine OLIVIER</strong> — then a student in his late teens in a
              <em>classe préparatoire</em> near Paris, fed up with a keyboard that fought him on every É
              and every quotation mark — started building his own fix. He has carried the project as a volunteer
              ever since: nine years of daily use, testing and refinement, first alone, and since 2026
              through the AMCF, the non-profit association he chairs.
            </p>
            <picture class="page-presse__story-media">
              <source srcset="/images/antoine-olivier-300.webp" type="image/webp">
              <img src="/images/antoine-olivier-300.png" alt="Antoine OLIVIER" width="150" height="150" loading="lazy" class="page-presse__story-photo">
            </picture>
          </div>
          <p class="mb-4 text-secondary">
            The bet: <strong>keep the AZERTY everyone already knows</strong> — same letters, same muscle
            memory — and fix only what is broken. The result, <strong>AZERTY Global</strong>, preserves
            99% of typing habits while finally making proper French (and 200+ other languages) easy to type.
            The final version was released to the public on <strong>June 15, 2026</strong>, free and open source.
          </p>

          <div class="alert alert--info">
            <p class="alert__title">💬 In his words</p>
            <p class="alert__text italic">
              "I was a student taking notes all day, and my own keyboard kept getting in the way —
              no É, no proper French quotation marks, even the period hidden behind Shift. Plenty of
              people had tried to fix the AZERTY before me, but almost always by piling extra characters
              onto it — never by also fixing its everyday flaws: the period, the @, the programming
              symbols, the acute and grave accents. So I set out to do both. Nine years later, I'm
              still at it."
            </p>
            <p class="alert__text text-sm font-semibold mt-2">— Antoine OLIVIER, creator of AZERTY Global</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Short bio -->
        <div class="card mb-6">
          <h3 class="card__title">👤 About Antoine Olivier</h3>
          <p class="card__text">
            Antoine Olivier, now in his twenties, started AZERTY Global in 2017 as a student in a French
            <em>classe préparatoire</em>. He is the creator of AZERTY Global and the president of the
            <strong>AMCF</strong> (Association pour la Modernisation du Clavier Français), the non-profit
            that maintains and distributes the layout. He has worked on the project as a volunteer for
            nine years. Based in Clermont-Ferrand, France. Interviews in English or French.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Timeline -->
        <div class="card">
          <h3 class="card__title">🗓️ Timeline</h3>
          <ul class="text-secondary pl-4 leading-loose">
            <li><strong>January 2016</strong> — A report commissioned by the French Ministry of Culture states that proper French cannot be typed on the AZERTY keyboard.</li>
            <li><strong>2017</strong> — Antoine Olivier, then a student, starts designing AZERTY Global.</li>
            <li><strong>2019</strong> — AFNOR publishes the official NF Z71-300 standard; its adoption remains marginal.</li>
            <li><strong>March 2026</strong> — The AMCF, a French non-profit association, is founded to maintain and distribute the project.</li>
            <li><strong>June 15, 2026</strong> — AZERTY Global is released as a final version: free, open source (EUPL 1.2), for Windows (including a Microsoft Store app), macOS and Linux.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
