    <!-- 3. Why this is a story: the broken keyboard, explained -->
    <section class="section">
      <div class="container container--narrow">
        <h2 class="mb-4">⌨️ The French keyboard problem, in 30 seconds</h2>

        <div class="bg-gradient-primary border-primary-1 card">
          <p class="section-lead mb-4">
            French grammar requires accented capitals (É, È, À, Ç), the œ ligature (<em>cœur</em>, <em>œuvre</em>)
            and the quotation marks « ». Yet on the AZERTY layout shipped with every computer in France since 1984,
            <strong>none of these can be typed directly</strong> — most French people work around their own
            keyboard every day with number codes, copy-pasting or spelling mistakes.
          </p>
          <p class="section-lead">
            <strong>AZERTY Global</strong> fixes this with <strong>only 5 improvements</strong>: type
            É, È, À, Ç directly with Caps Lock, use « » and œ, and reach the programming
            symbols { } [ ] easily — while 99% of typing habits stay untouched. No new hardware,
            no relearning, no cost.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h3 class="text-center mt-8 mb-2">How the French cope today</h3>
        <p class="text-center mb-6 text-secondary">
          Forty years of daily workarounds — each one a scene for your story.
        </p>

        <div class="benefits__grid gap-4">
          <div class="card text-center">
            <div class="mb-2 text-2rem">🔢</div>
            <h3 class="card__title">Alt codes</h3>
            <p class="card__text">Hold Alt, type 0201 on the numeric keypad, release: É. This is the method documented by Microsoft's support pages and regularly taught by the French press — and it is impossible on most laptops, which have no numeric keypad.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card text-center">
            <div class="mb-2 text-2rem">🔎</div>
            <h3 class="card__title">Googling your own language</h3>
            <p class="card__text">Queries about typing a capital É alone («&nbsp;é majuscule&nbsp;») represent some 150,000 Google searches every month in France — people searching the web to copy-paste letters of their own alphabet.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card text-center">
            <div class="mb-2 text-2rem">✍️</div>
            <h3 class="card__title">Autocorrect</h3>
            <p class="card__text">Word silently fixes some of it (Ecole → École). Browsers, email clients, chat apps and forms don't — so the fix disappears exactly where most typing happens today.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card text-center">
            <div class="mb-2 text-2rem">🛠️</div>
            <h3 class="card__title">Power-user utilities</h3>
            <p class="card__text">The tech-savvy install third-party tools such as WinCompose to compose characters key by key — a fine workaround, for the few who know it exists.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-center mt-6 text-secondary">
          AZERTY Global replaces all of these with simple keystrokes, directly on the keyboard — that's the story.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

